# Chapter 7 — African drums

African drum traditions are conversations. Djembe, dundun, talking drum — each drum has a voice, a role in the ensemble, and language of its own.

A djembe circle isn't accompaniment. It's a conversation happening in three or four voices at once. The rhythm is the sentence; the drums are the speakers.

## The roster

```scheme
(define african-drums
  '((djembe        goblet-shaped  hand-played)
    (dundun        cylindrical    stick-played)
    (talking-drum  hourglass     pitch-bending)
    (djun-djun     bass          stick-played)
    (sabar         hand-and-stick medium)))

(for-each (lambda (d) (display d) (newline)) african-drums)
```

Output:

```
(djembe goblet-shaped hand-played)
(dundun cylindrical stick-played)
(talking-drum hourglass pitch-bending)
(djun-djun bass stick-played)
(sabar hand-and-stick medium)
```

## Three djembe strokes

```scheme
(define (djembe-stroke type)
  (case type
    ((bass) '(low-thud full-palm-center))
    ((tone) '(mid-warm-fingertips-edge))
    ((slap) '(bright-crack-fingertips-hard-edge))))

(display (djembe-stroke 'bass)) (newline)
(display (djembe-stroke 'tone)) (newline)
(display (djembe-stroke 'slap)) (newline)
```

Output:

```
(low-thud full-palm-center)
(mid-warm-fingertips-edge)
(bright-crack-fingertips-hard-edge)
```

Three strokes, three timbres, one drum.

## A basic djembe pattern

```scheme
(define (make-pattern beats) (list 'pattern beats))

(define kuku
  (make-pattern
    '(bass rest tone tone
      bass rest slap slap
      tone tone rest bass
      slap tone rest bass)))

(display kuku) (newline)
```

Output:

```
(pattern (bass rest tone tone bass rest slap slap tone tone rest bass slap tone rest bass))
```

The Kuku rhythm — a common introductory djembe pattern.

## The talking drum

Pitch-bending drums can carry actual speech.

```scheme
(define (talking-drum-say phrase)
  (list 'talking-drum 'says phrase 'via 'pitch-bend))

(display (talking-drum-say '(rising-question-tone))) (newline)
(display (talking-drum-say '(falling-statement-tone))) (newline)
```

Output:

```
(talking-drum says (rising-question-tone) via pitch-bend)
(talking-drum says (falling-statement-tone) via pitch-bend)
```

The head tension changes as the drum is squeezed against the body — pitch rises and falls. In Yoruba tradition, it mirrors the tonal shape of speech.

## Ensemble roles

```scheme
(define (drum-role drum)
  (case drum
    ((djembe)       'lead-voice-improvisation)
    ((dundun)       'timeline-and-groove)
    ((djun-djun)    'bass-heartbeat)
    ((talking-drum) 'speech-signal-melody)))

(display (drum-role 'djembe))       (newline)
(display (drum-role 'djun-djun))    (newline)
```

Output:

```
lead-voice-improvisation
bass-heartbeat
```

## A three-drum arrangement

```scheme
(define (arrangement)
  '((djun-djun    heartbeat     bass)
    (dundun       timeline      mid)
    (djembe       lead-voice    high)))

(for-each (lambda (a) (display a) (newline)) (arrangement))
```

Output:

```
(djun-djun heartbeat bass)
(dundun timeline mid)
(djembe lead-voice high)
```

Three drums, three roles, three registers. Together, one conversation.

## What you know now

- African drum ensembles are conversations, not accompaniment.
- Djembe has bass/tone/slap strokes.
- Talking drum bends pitch to mirror speech.
- Roles cluster: heartbeat / timeline / lead voice.

## Try before you turn the page

```scheme
(display (list 'the 'djembe 'lead 'and 'the 'djun-djun 'bass 'are 'the 'top 'and 'bottom 'of 'the 'conversation)) (newline)
```

If you can place three drums in three roles, you're ready for tabla.

